<subSubSection pageNumber="738" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="738">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="738">Note:</emphasis>
This name has been out of use for many years. From 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeusâ€™">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
lengthy description, he evidently had material available to him but this is now lost. It seems very likely that this name referred to the same species which Linnaeus described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. Br." baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Phlomis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="zeylanica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="738">P. zeylanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 1753, and a 
<typeStatus>neotype</typeStatus>
was chosen by Paton to formalise this, with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Phlomis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="738">P. indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
falling into the synonymy of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="738">
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. Br." baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Leucas" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="zeylanica">L. zeylanica</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
